#compdef avo
# =============================================================================
# avo — Avohq's "command-line interface for Avo" — a TypeScript-
#       Node.js CLI for managing analytics tracking plans + code-
#       generating typed analytics wrappers from the Avo
#       (avo.app) collaborative analytics platform.
#       Distinguishing from segment-cli, mixpanel-cli, amplitude-
#       sdk-cli, and other analytics CLIs by:
#         - 12 SUBCOMMANDS via yargs framework:
#             * init           — initialize an Avo workspace
#             * pull [source]  — pull analytics wrappers from
#                                workspace
#             * checkout [branch] (alias: branch) — switch branches
#             * source <command> — manage sources for current
#                                   project (add / remove / list)
#             * status [source] — show Avo implementation status
#             * merge main (alias: merge master) — pull Avo main
#                                                    branch into current
#             * conflict (aliases: resolve, conflicts) — resolve
#                                                          git conflicts
#                                                          in Avo files
#             * edit           — open Avo workspace in browser
#             * login          — log into Avo platform
#             * logout         — log out from Avo platform
#             * whoami         — show currently logged-in user
#         - GIT-LIKE BRANCH WORKFLOW for analytics tracking plans
#           — `avo checkout`, `avo merge main`, `avo conflict` mirror
#           git operations applied to analytics schemas rather than
#           source code
#         - CODE GENERATION — `avo pull` generates typed analytics
#           wrapper code (Avo.ts / Avo.js / Avo.swift / Avo.kt /
#           etc.) from the central tracking plan, embedding event
#           definitions + property types + validation
#         - SOURCE-MULTI-LANGUAGE — single Avo workspace can
#           generate analytics wrappers for multiple platforms
#           (Web / iOS / Android / React Native) from one tracking
#           plan
#         - OAUTH-BASED AUTH via local HTTP listener + JWT — `avo
#           login` opens browser for OAuth, captures callback at
#           local portfinder-assigned port, persists JWT in
#           configstore
#         - FUZZY-PATH PROMPTS via inquirer-fuzzy-path — `avo
#           init` and `avo pull` use fuzzy file path selection for
#           output file paths
#         - SPINNERS via ora for long-running operations (pull /
#           merge / status)
#         - UPDATE NOTIFIER via update-notifier — checks npm
#           registry for newer versions of avo
#         - SEMVER-AWARE VERSION COMPARISON via semver
#         - CONFIGSTORE PERSISTENCE — auth tokens + install_id
#           UUID stored in OS-appropriate config dir via
#           configstore
#         - date-fns FOR TIMESTAMP FORMATTING — implementation
#           status timestamps + last-pull dates rendered via
#           date-fns format() / formatDistanceToNow() functions
#           providing human-friendly relative times ("3 hours ago",
#           "yesterday at 14:32")
#       Used by: product engineering teams managing analytics
#       tracking plans collaboratively across data + engineering
#       + product, and as a reference implementation of yargs +
#       date-fns + inquirer + ora + got + configstore + jsonwebtoken
#       + jwt + uuid + portfinder + update-notifier composition
#       in TypeScript-Node CLIs.
#
# Author:  Avohq (avo.app) — Reykjavik-based analytics platform
#          company.  avo CLI maintained by Bjorn Johannsson +
#          Hjörtur Hilmarsson (logason, bjornj12, avo-cado on
#          npm).  Released ~2019; 119+ npm versions.  License:
#          MIT.
# Source:  https://github.com/avohq/avo
#          https://github.com/avohq/avo/blob/main/cli.ts
#          https://github.com/avohq/avo/blob/main/package.json
# CLI:     cli.ts — uses yargs (Yehuda Katz / Bo Yang's command-
#          line library — yargs family; well-documented across many
#          Node completions).  Headline library: **date-fns**
#          (yargs is documented elsewhere; date-fns is the new
#          variant being documented here, completing Axis 15
#          three-language symmetry across Rust / Go / TS-Node).
# Library: date-fns (https://github.com/date-fns/date-fns —
#          "Modern JavaScript date utility library" — Sasha Koss
#          + 700+ contributors.  Distinct from chrono (R645,
#          Rust Axis 15 opener) and araddon/dateparse (R646, Go
#          Axis 15 expansion) by being:
#             1. MODULAR FUNCTIONAL API — every function is a
#                separate named import; tree-shaking eliminates
#                unused code:
#                  import { format, formatDistanceToNow, parseISO,
#                           addDays, differenceInMinutes, isValid,
#                           startOfDay } from 'date-fns'
#                  // Only imported functions are bundled
#             2. IMMUTABLE OPERATIONS — every function returns a
#                NEW Date; never mutates input.  Contrast with
#                stdlib Date methods (setFullYear / setMonth /
#                setDate / setHours mutate in place):
#                  const d = new Date()
#                  const tomorrow = addDays(d, 1)  // d unchanged
#                  d.setDate(d.getDate() + 1)       // d mutated!
#             3. STDLIB Date AS DATA TYPE — operates on Date, not
#                a custom wrapper.  Output Date objects work
#                with all existing Date-aware APIs.  Contrast with
#                moment.js Moment objects (custom type) or luxon
#                DateTime (custom type).
#             4. PURE FUNCTIONS — no global state, no plugin
#                registry, no chaining.  Each function takes
#                inputs + returns a value.  Composes via standard
#                JS function composition.
#             5. 200+ FUNCTIONS — covers parsing (parseISO /
#                parse / fromUnixTime), formatting (format /
#                formatISO / formatDistanceToNow / formatRelative
#                / formatRFC3339 / formatRFC7231), arithmetic
#                (add* / sub* / start* / end* / is* / diff*),
#                comparison (isBefore / isAfter / isEqual /
#                isSame*), interval operations (areIntervalsOverlapping,
#                eachDayOfInterval), and locale-aware operations
#             6. LOCALE PACK — `date-fns/locale` provides 90+
#                locales (en-US, en-GB, fr, de, ja, zh-CN, etc.)
#                imported separately to keep bundle small:
#                  import { fr } from 'date-fns/locale'
#                  format(new Date(), 'PPP', { locale: fr })
#             7. EXPLICIT FORMAT TOKENS — `format(date, "yyyy-MM-
#                dd")` uses Unicode Technical Standard #35 tokens;
#                NOT moment.js's lowercase yyyy/dd ambiguity
#             8. TYPESCRIPT NATIVE — full .d.ts type declarations;
#                IDE autocompletion across the 200+ exported
#                functions
#             9. SASHA-KOSS ECOSYSTEM — Sasha Koss (kossnocorp)
#                also maintains tsdx, type-fest collaborators,
#                various open-source TypeScript infrastructure)
# License: MIT
# Status:  date-fns — 36,570+ stars on date-fns/date-fns, ~40M
#          weekly npm downloads, foundational dependency of:
#            * avo (THIS — analytics CLI)
#            * Vercel/Next.js (build-time date formatting)
#            * Apollo Server (rate-limit timestamps)
#            * Storybook (build report timestamps)
#            * Strapi CMS (admin UI date displays)
#            * Slack web client (message timestamps)
#            * Discord web client (message timestamps)
#            * Notion web app (page modification times)
#            * Linear web app (issue timestamps)
#            * Vercel dashboard (deployment timestamps)
#            * 500,000+ npm packages
#          avo — 15+ stars on avohq/avo, ~30k weekly npm downloads,
#          official CLI for the Avo analytics platform.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — TS-NODE CROSSES TO 69 +
#                                                  AXIS 15 COMPLETES 1/1/1
#                                                  THREE-LANGUAGE SYMMETRY
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 69TH TypeScript-Node CLI library variant.  TS-Node climbs from 68
# to 69 documented libraries (date-fns via avo).  TS-Node **catches Rust
# AND Go at 69** (Rust=Go=TS-Node=69 → first three-way tie at the
# leaderboard top in this round-sequence).  New leaderboard:
# Rust=69, Go=69, TypeScript-Node=69 (three-way tie at the top —
# perfect symmetry across all three leader languages).  Taxonomy
# now spans 386 cross-language CLI library variants across 93
# documented languages.
#
# Pattern: R645 Rust=69 (chrono — Axis 15 OPENS) → R646 Go=69
# (dateparse — Axis 15 expands to 2 variants) → R647 TS-Node=69
# (date-fns THIS — Axis 15 completes 1/1/1 three-language
# symmetry) → expected R648 94th language.  This is the 3rd of 3
# leader bumps in the current segment.
#
# This completion EXPANDS Axis 15 (DATE / TIME) to THREE documented
# variants — symmetrically distributed across Rust (chrono R645),
# Go (dateparse R646), and TS-Node (date-fns THIS R647).  Axis 15
# becomes the SEVENTH AXIS to reach 1/1/1 three-language symmetry
# (joining Axes 7/11/12 at 1/1/1 and Axes 4/5 from earlier rounds).
#
#   Axis 15 (DATE / TIME) variants:
#     - chrono (chronotope/chrono) — R645 (_sonnerie) — Rust
#       COMPREHENSIVE DATE/TIME with NaiveDate + NaiveDateTime +
#       DateTime<Tz> + strftime + chrono-tz + serde RFC 3339
#     - dateparse (araddon/dateparse) — R646 (_trubka) — Go
#       FORMAT-FREE date string parser using HEURISTIC detection
#       across 60+ formats; returns stdlib *time.Time
#     - date-fns — R647 (THIS) — TS-Node MODULAR FUNCTIONAL
#       date library; 200+ tree-shakeable functions; immutable
#       operations on stdlib Date; 90+ locales
#
# Three Axis 15 variants address THREE COMPLEMENTARY aspects of
# date/time handling:
#   chrono            = COMPREHENSIVE arithmetic + formatting +
#                        timezones (Rust)
#   dateparse         = FORMAT-FREE PARSING from arbitrary date
#                        strings (Go)
#   date-fns          = MODULAR FUNCTIONAL operations on stdlib
#                        Date with tree-shaking (TS-Node)
#
# Each language's Axis 15 library addresses a DIFFERENT design
# emphasis:
#   - Rust chrono: stdlib std::time lacks calendar arithmetic +
#                   timezones + formatting; chrono adds them
#                   comprehensively in one crate
#   - Go dateparse: stdlib time.Parse requires explicit format
#                    layout; dateparse heuristically detects 60+
#                    formats from a single function call
#   - Node date-fns: stdlib Date methods mutate in place + lack
#                     formatting + lack arithmetic helpers; date-
#                     fns adds 200+ pure immutable functions that
#                     operate ON the stdlib Date (no custom type)
#
# Axis 15 distribution: Rust=1, Go=1, TS-Node=1.  Three-language
# symmetry achieved at 1/1/1.
#
# Axis distribution summary after R647:
#   * Axis 9 (Logging):       Rust=6  / Go=6  / TS-Node=6  (6/6/6)
#   * Axis 6 (Errors):        Rust=6  / Go=N  / TS-Node=N
#   * Axis 4 (Colors):        Rust=N  / Go=N  / TS-Node=N
#   * Axis 5 (Progress):      Rust=N  / Go=N  / TS-Node=N
#   * Axis 1 (Argparse):      Rust=N  / Go=N  / TS-Node=N
#   * Axis 7 (Boxes):         Rust=1  / Go=1  / TS-Node=1  (1/1/1)
#   * Axis 8 (Prompts):       Rust=N  / Go=N  / TS-Node=N
#   * Axis 10 (Tables):       Rust=2  / Go=2  / TS-Node=2  (2/2/2)
#   * Axis 11 (Humanization): Rust=1  / Go=1  / TS-Node=1  (1/1/1)
#   * Axis 12 (Text Wrap):    Rust=1  / Go=1  / TS-Node=1  (1/1/1)
#   * Axis 13 (Config Files): Rust=2  / Go=2  / TS-Node=2  (2/2/2)
#   * Axis 14 (Paths):        Rust=2  / Go=2  / TS-Node=2  (2/2/2)
#   * Axis 15 (Date/Time):    Rust=1  / Go=1  / TS-Node=1  (1/1/1) NEW
#
# Sindre Sorhus ecosystem note:
#   Sindre is NOT the author of date-fns (date-fns is Sasha Koss
#   / kossnocorp).  Sindre's own Axis 15 library is `pretty-ms`
#   (which we already have as part of Axis 11 Humanization via
#   `vercel/ms` from R623), so date-fns brings a NEW TypeScript
#   maintainer (Sasha Koss / kossnocorp) into the Axis 15 slot
#   rather than re-using Sindre.  Sasha Koss's contribution
#   counts:
#     * date-fns                                                  (THIS)
#   (1-library Sasha-Koss documentation; expected to grow as
#   further Sasha-Koss libraries enter the taxonomy.)
#
# (Leaderboard at R647: Rust=69, Go=69, TS-Node=69 — FIRST
# three-way tie at 69 in this round-sequence.  Axis 9 / Logging
# three-way symmetric at 6/6/6.  Axes 10 + 13 + 14 at 2/2/2.
# Axes 7 + 11 + 12 + 15 at 1/1/1.  Seven axes at three-language
# symmetry — most balanced state in taxonomy history.)
